{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chapter-level-2-chapter-level-2-tsx","path":"/topics/burns-scalds/diagnosis/differential-diagnosis/","result":{"pageContext":{"chapter":{"id":"ee84e8db-8e06-55e4-bf7c-c267469d4e69","slug":"differential-diagnosis","fullItemName":"Differential diagnosis","depth":2,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field f1ee57c6-302c-4e5d-b985-ddd3cc6a8710 --><h2>What else might it be?</h2><!-- end field f1ee57c6-302c-4e5d-b985-ddd3cc6a8710 -->","summary":"","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item 54bc4e94-3aa4-4fda-b139-e22a31b1a9aa --><!-- begin field 4b3a9206-b0b9-4b9c-98cf-be0f3366b45e --><p><strong>Alternative conditions which may present similarly to burns and scalds include:</strong></p><ul><li>Blistering skin diseases — such as Stevens-Johnson syndrome, staphylococcal scalded skin syndrome, toxic epidermal necrolysis, or bullous impetigo. See the CKS topic on <a class=\"topic-reference external-reference\" href=\"/topics/impetigo/\">Impetigo</a> for more information.</li><li>Cellulitis — see the CKS topic on <a class=\"topic-reference external-reference\" href=\"/topics/cellulitis-acute/\">Cellulitis - acute</a> for more information.</li><li>Photodermatitis — sun exposure following chemical contact with, for example, perfume or plant oils such as citrus or wild parsnip. May present as initial skin erythema leading to blistering lesions which follow the pattern of contact with the chemical in sun-exposed areas of skin.</li><li>Hypersensitivity reactions — for example to detergents, shampoo, or laxatives.</li><li>Skin necrosis — for example caused by pressure.</li><li>Congenital curvilinear palpable hyperpigmentation (rare) — occurs spontaneously from one month after birth; presents as symmetrical, loop-like raised areas of skin on the posterior calves.</li></ul><!-- end field 4b3a9206-b0b9-4b9c-98cf-be0f3366b45e --><!-- end item 54bc4e94-3aa4-4fda-b139-e22a31b1a9aa -->","topic":{"id":"6d61b3b5-8426-5dd8-9876-7eb2344b5667","topicId":"bd40ad7e